large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":23,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alexander Neville was born in 1359, in Thornton Bridge, Yorkshire, England, his father, Ralph Neville, was 27 and his mother, Elizabeth Leeds, was 27. He married Margery before October 1392. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1410, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1359–about 1410":"1359–umbes 1410","1357–1372":"1357–1372","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1362–1425":"1362–1425","1390–1457":"1390–1457","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1332–1368":"1332–1368","1333–1390":"1333–1390","about 1390":"umbes 1390","abt 1390":"umbes 1390","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1359":"1359","before October 1392":"enne oktoobrit 1392","1425":"1425","1457":"1457","1368":"1368","1357":"1357","1333":"1333","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","about 1356":"umbes 1356","about 1368":"umbes 1368","about 1410":"umbes 1410","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornton Bridge, Yorkshire, England":"Thornton Bridge, Yorkshire, England","Gipton, Yorkshire, England":"Gipton, Yorkshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdo